Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/network-capture.ts (add one cleanupThrottle call in onDetach)

Context:
The chrome.debugger.onDetach handler (lines 435-444) cleans up interception and emulation state but NOT throttle state. The chrome.tabs.onRemoved handler (lines 420-430) DOES call all three: cleanupInterception, cleanupEmulation, cleanupThrottle. This is an inconsistency that violates the documented contract of cleanupThrottle ('called when tab is closed or debugger detaches').

The cleanupThrottle import is already present in network-capture.ts at the top of the file:
  import { cleanupThrottle } from './browser-commands/throttle-commands.js';

Current onDetach handler:
```
chrome.debugger.onDetach.addListener((source: chrome.debugger.Debuggee, _reason: string) => {
  const tabId = source.tabId;
  if (tabId !== undefined) {
    cleanupInterception(tabId);
    cleanupEmulation(tabId);
    const state = captures.get(tabId);
    if (state) clearInterval(state.pruneIntervalId);
    captures.delete(tabId);
  }
});
```

After fix:
```
chrome.debugger.onDetach.addListener((source: chrome.debugger.Debuggee, _reason: string) => {
  const tabId = source.tabId;
  if (tabId !== undefined) {
    cleanupInterception(tabId);
    cleanupEmulation(tabId);
    cleanupThrottle(tabId);
    const state = captures.get(tabId);
    if (state) clearInterval(state.pruneIntervalId);
    captures.delete(tabId);
  }
});
```

Constraints:
- Do NOT add cleanupThrottle to any other place — only the onDetach handler is missing it
- Do NOT change the onRemoved handler (it already has all three cleanup calls)
- The import line is already present — do NOT add a duplicate import

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/App.tsx (fix .catch handler)
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/FailedPluginCard.tsx (add error display if not already present; read this file first)
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/PluginList.tsx (may need to thread failedPluginErrors through; read this file first)

Context:
Current handleRemoveFailedPlugin (App.tsx ~lines 220-237):
```
const handleRemoveFailedPlugin = (specifier: string) => {
  setRemovingFailedPlugins(prev => new Set([...prev, specifier]));
  removeFailedPlugin(specifier)
    .then(() => {
      setRemovingFailedPlugins(prev => {
        const next = new Set(prev);
        next.delete(specifier);
        return next;
      });
    })
    .catch(() => {
      setRemovingFailedPlugins(prev => {
        const next = new Set(prev);
        next.delete(specifier);
        return next;
      });
    });
};
```

The existing pattern for regular plugin errors uses showPluginError (pluginName, message) which adds to a pluginErrors Map and auto-clears after 5s. FailedPluginCard currently has no analogous prop.

Recommended approach:
1. Add a failedPluginErrors Map<string, string> state in App.tsx, mirroring pluginErrors
2. Add a showFailedPluginError (specifier, message) helper function
3. Call showFailedPluginError in the .catch handler
4. Thread failedPluginErrors through PluginList to FailedPluginCard
5. FailedPluginCard renders the error when present

Alternative (simpler if FailedPluginCard already has an actionError or similar prop):
Read FailedPluginCard.tsx first to check what props it accepts, then use the simplest available mechanism.

Constraints:
- The .catch handler MUST still clear the removing state — do NOT remove setRemovingFailedPlugins from catch
- Follow the same auto-dismiss pattern (ERROR_DISPLAY_DURATION_MS from side-panel/constants.ts) used by showPluginError
- Do NOT change how successful removal works

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/BrowserToolsCard.tsx (replace preToggleRef with Map-based rollback)

Context:
Current handleToolPermissionChange in BrowserToolsCard.tsx (lines 95-106):
```
const handleToolPermissionChange = (toolName: string, newPermission: ToolPermission) => {
  const myVersion = ++toggleCounter.current;
  onToolsChange(prev => {
    preToggleRef.current = prev;  // BUG: shared ref overwritten by concurrent calls
    return prev.map(t => (t.name === toolName ? { ...t, permission: newPermission } : t));
  });
  void setToolPermission('browser', toolName, newPermission).catch(() => {
    if (toggleCounter.current === myVersion) {
      onToolsChange(() => preToggleRef.current);  // BUG: may use wrong pre-state
    }
    showToggleError(`Failed to update ${toolName}`);
  });
};
```

The existing preToggleRef is declared at line 71: `const preToggleRef = useRef<BrowserToolState[]>([]);`

Reference implementation: PluginCard.tsx uses this pattern correctly:
```
const pendingToolRollbacks = useRef<Map<number, { toolName: string; prev: ToolPermission }>>(new Map());

const applyToolPermission = (toolName: string, newPermission: ToolPermission) => {
  const myVersion = ++toggleCounter.current;
  const currentPerm = pluginTools.find(t => t.name === toolName)?.permission ?? 'off';
  pendingToolRollbacks.current.set(myVersion, { toolName, prev: currentPerm });
  updatePluginTools(prev => prev.map(t => (t.name === toolName ? { ...t, permission: newPermission } : t)));
  void setToolPermission(plugin.name, toolName, newPermission)
    .catch(() => {
      const rollback = pendingToolRollbacks.current.get(myVersion);
      if (rollback) {
        updatePluginTools(prev =>
          prev.map(t => (t.name === rollback.toolName ? { ...t, permission: rollback.prev } : t)),
        );
      }
      showToggleError(`Failed to update ${toolName}`);
    })
    .finally(() => {
      pendingToolRollbacks.current.delete(myVersion);
    });
};
```

Apply the same Map-based pattern to BrowserToolsCard.handleToolPermissionChange. Instead of storing the entire tools array in preToggleRef, store {toolName, prev: ToolPermission} per version.

Constraints:
- preToggleRef may become unused after this change — remove it if so
- Keep showToggleError(...) call in the .catch — error display must not regress
- Do NOT change handleBrowserPermissionChange (which uses preBrowserPermRef — it is correct since it stores a scalar permission value, not an array)
- The toggleCounter ref is shared across both browser permission and tool permission changes — do NOT change this

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/background-message-handlers.ts (fix handlePluginReadinessChanged)

Context:
All registered handlers in the backgroundHandlers Map have the listener return true (line 826 in background-message-handlers.ts). This tells Chrome to keep the message port open awaiting sendResponse. handlePluginReadinessChanged is the only handler that never calls sendResponse — it uses `_sendResponse` (underscore = intentionally unused).

Current code (approximately lines 338-348):
```
const handlePluginReadinessChanged: MessageHandler = (message, _sendResponse) => {
  const plugin = message.plugin;
  if (typeof plugin !== 'string' || plugin === '') return;

  (async () => {
    const meta = await getPluginMeta(plugin);
    if (!meta) return;
    await notifyAffectedPlugins([meta]);
  })().catch((err: unknown) => {
    console.warn('[opentabs] handlePluginReadinessChanged failed:', err);
  });
};
```

Fix: rename _sendResponse to sendResponse and call it immediately (fire-and-forget):
```
const handlePluginReadinessChanged: MessageHandler = (message, sendResponse) => {
  const plugin = message.plugin;
  sendResponse({ ok: true });  // Release port immediately — async work runs in background
  if (typeof plugin !== 'string' || plugin === '') return;

  (async () => {
    const meta = await getPluginMeta(plugin);
    if (!meta) return;
    await notifyAffectedPlugins([meta]);
  })().catch((err: unknown) => {
    console.warn('[opentabs] handlePluginReadinessChanged failed:', err);
  });
};
```

Note: sendResponse({ ok: true }) is called BEFORE the plugin string validation check on purpose — we always want to release the port regardless. Move sendResponse before the if-guard.

Constraints:
- Do NOT await the async IIFE before calling sendResponse — call it immediately
- Do NOT change what the async IIFE does (getPluginMeta + notifyAffectedPlugins)
- Do NOT add sendResponse calls to any other handler — only handlePluginReadinessChanged is missing it
